abc news wouldnt have used former secretary of 
state henry kissinger as a paid expert on a china special last june 
had it known of his business ties there a spokeswoman said friday 
however l paul bremer a kissinger business associate said 
there was no conflict of interest in kissingers appearance on the 
broadcast on it kissinger was asked about possible us military 
sanctions against china for its violence against the studentled 
demonstrations in beijing 
in his reply the former secretary of state in the ford and nixon 
administrations stressed the importance of us relations with the 
beijing regime i wouldnt do any sanctions he told anchor 
peter jennings 
kissinger at the time was appearing under a special agreement 
with abc that he terminated wednesday after his election as a board 
member of cbs inc 
the abc deal struck in 1982 paid him as a consultant and gave 
abc the right to interview him first on any of its broadcasts 
including world news tonight and ted koppels nightline but 
only on breaking stories 
he wasnt paid for appearances as a guest on these shows 
including as nightline and world news tonight when his 
interviews didnt concern breaking news said abc spokeswoman elise 
adde 
had abc news known of his business ties in china she said we 
would not have had him on that broadcast in june 
kissinger has extensive business interests in china including 
the establishment of a 75 million fund to be raised from us 
investors for joint ventures with the merchant banking arm of the 
chinese government the wall street journal reported friday 
in addition his consulting firm kissinger associates counsels 
several businesses on how to conduct operations overseas and 
specifically in their dealings with china the journal reported 
kissingers remarks on the june special were not motivated by 
commercial concerns said bremer state department employee for 23 
years now a senior partner in kissinger associates inc an 
international consulting firm 
kissingers remarks on issues like the situation in china last 
june are solely based on what he thinks are the us nations 
interest said bremer a former us ambassador 
kissingers abc deal was not his first with a network news 
division he previously had worked for nbcs news division after 
after his white house service 
since 1977 he has been a member of the american federation of 
radio and television artists but under the unions news contract 
with networks according union membership rolls 
aftra represents onair news correspondents and anchors at cbs 
nbc and abc the news contract and the entertainers contract 
stipulate different pay scales 
kissinger was busy friday and was not available for comment 
bremer said 
his election to the 14member cbs board was by a unanimous vote 
a source election said friday cbs policy is not to comment on 
internal board matters 
as a cbs board member kissinger will paid the same as other 
board members 22000 annually and 750 for each meeting he 
attends cbs spokesman george schweitzer said 
there is no contract that would make kissinger exclusive to cbs 
news and his board membership has absolutely nothing to do with 
cbs onair appearances schweitzer said 
in that regard he said referring to news matters he is 
henry kissinger private citizen and businessman and he can be 
