<TEXT>
after 9 months as prime minister 
benazir bhutto sees herself as a crusader to save pakistan from the 
clutches of drugs ethnic violence and rancorous politics 
i see things in terms of knights in shining armor trying to 
root out evil ms bhutto said in an interview with the associated 
press 
that may be a sort of simplistic way to put it but i am an 
optimist i have great dreams for my country and i want to achieve 
them 
but she acknowledged her vision might be a bit fanciful 
i think i am too much of an idealist 
educated at harvard and englands oxford university the 
36yearold ms bhutto is the first woman to lead a moslem nation 
and as she spoke she had a scarf called a dupatta draped over 
her shoulder when in public she wears the scarf over her head the 
custom of moslem women as a concession to pakistans religious 
right wing a powerful minority that opposes female rule 
ms bhutto and her leftleaning pakistan peoples party govern a 
restless nation of 107 million people burdened by poverty 
illiteracy and civil war across the border in afghanistan 
she said death threats after her government declared war on the 
heroin trade and drug barons have forced her to think of her safety 
something she has resisted since assuming office dec 2 
i dont believe in a life that is crowded with security she 
said i think its kind of nice to be able to slip away after 
having worked hard for a few days to be able to go for a half an 
hour walk 
i just consider it important for a person in public life to try 
and maintain a sense of normalacy to have their feet on the 
ground 
as for the drug war she said we are really now just going 
after the big people but its a much bigger problem its just 
proliferated all over the country like a cancer 
western countries estimate that up to 80 percent of the heroin 
arriving in the united states and europe comes from pakistan drug 
addiction in pakistan has soared from near zero in 1979 to an 
estimated 1 million addicts in 1989 
ms bhutto is also doing battle with an opposition made up of 
islamic fundamentalists conservatives and loyalists of the late 
president gen mohammad zia ulhaq and his military government 
zia overthrew her father prime minister zulfikar ali bhutto in 
a 1977 coup and had him hanged two years later for his alleged 
complicity in a murder plot 
zia many of his top generals and us ambassador arnold l 
raphel died in a mysterious plane crash in august 1988 clearing the 
way for pakistans first free elections in more than a decade and 
resulting in mrs bhuttos election nov 16 
ms bhutto says the most serious threat to her government is 
ethnic hundreds of pakistanis have died and thousands have been 
injured since 1986 in violence in her southern home province of 
sindh in fighting among militant secessionists indian moslem 
immigrants and internal migrants from poorer provinces 
during general zias time ethnic groups became very strong 
she said they set up armed camps and they trained their people 
so its a situation of almost a minikind of a guerrilla war its 
not a guerrilla war against the government but its almost a state 
of anarchy and a rebellion against authority 
ms bhutto claims that her rightwing political opposition the 
nineparty islamic democratic alliance has had a hand in the sindh 
violence 
she also has implicated neighboring india in the sindh troubles 
india and pakistan have fought three wars since they became 
independent from britain in 1947 and they routinely accuse each 
other of fueling their internal problems 
to the west ms bhutto inherited pakistans sponsorship of 
moslem guerrillas fighting to oust the sovietbacked government of 
afghanistan 
more than 3 million afghan war refugees huddle in camps dotting 
pakistans western frontier 
pakistan cant afford to keep the refugees she said but 
are the refugees going to go back without political stability 
so far we have not seen any message or any method that would 
enable the emergence of an independent afghanistan or the return of 
the afghan refugees those remain our goals 
she also said her political opposition is doomed because of its 
links to the zia era when pakistan was under martial law and 
political parties were barred from elections 
pakistan just cant afford a return to the decade of 
repression she said all those who are patriots in the 
different sectors of life whether it is civilian or military 
recognize that therefore i see no imminent threat to democracy in 
pakistan 
but she added that law and order cannot survive without economic 
development in a country where the average yearly wage is under 400 
first youve got to try and create a system create a rule of 
law which gives security and side by side youve got to have 
economic improvement and opportunitiees so people can give better 
meaning to their lives she said 
</TEXT>
