<TEXT>
the former president of an indianapolis generic 
drug manufacturer who paid 32000 in bribes to three us food and 
drug administration officials has been fined 250000 and ordered to 
serve a year working for the american cancer society 
dilip p shah 43 formerly of quad pharmaceuticals inc was 
convicted of bribing fda officials in exchange for their 
recommendations for approval of quad products 
in addition to the community service and fine us district 
judge john r hargrove also sentenced shah on wednesday to 60 days 
in jail and imposed two years of probation after the defendant 
completes his prison time 
assistant us attorney gary p jordan said shah paid 23000 
worth in illegal gratuities to charles y chang former branch chief 
of the fdas division of generic drugs 8000 in cash to david 
brancato an fda review chemist and 1000 in department store gift 
certificates to walter kletch another agency chemist 
jordan said shahs cooperation in the case helped prosecutors 
convict kletch and brancato chang also has pleaded guilty in the 
case 
so far the investigation has resulted in the convictions of the 
three fda officials and three pharmaceutical company officials two 
companies also have been found guilty of criminal wrongdoing and are 
facing heavy fines 
jordan said additional charges are expected as the investigation 
continues 
</TEXT>
