marketing year on june 1 was about 694 million bushels down from 
1261 billion bushels on june 1 1988 and 1821 billion bushels on 
june 1 1987 
according to usda projections the carryover may be down to 494 
million bushels by next june 1 despite a larger harvest this year 
demand for wheat continues to outstrip production 
department analysts say the 1990 option is expected to boost the 
acreage for harvest by 21 million acres to an estimated 696 
million acres as a result they say the 1990 harvest would rise 
only 66 million bushels to 2596 billion bushels 
the national association of wheat growers was less critical of 
the usda announcement but association president reggie wyckoff said 
us export efforts should be stepped up if plantings increase 
producers want to be assured that they wont be caught holding 
a mountain of surplus grain if this experiment fails wyckoff a 
genoa colo wheat farmer said in a statement issued by the 
associations washington office 
