anheuserbusch must pay 1 million in fines 
for illegally discharging phosphoruscontaminated water into the 
seneca river officials said 
the beer maker also admitted its employees reported false 
sampling data to the state department of environmental conservation 
and hid from dec inspectors hoses that illegally bypassed critical 
portions of the waste water treatment system 
in an agreement disclosed thursday the st louisbased brewer 
agreed to pay a 925000 civil fine for unlawful discharges into the 
seneca river from its plant in baldwinsville ny said new york 
attorney general robert abrams 
on wednesday night the company pleaded guilty in lysander town 
court to three misdemeanor violations of the states water pollution 
control regulations and was fined 75000 
the company also agreed to publish fullpage advertisements in 
four waste water treatment trade publications advising other 
corporations to comply with state environmental standards in 
addition the company will undergo an independent audit of its 
treatment plant operations 
walter a suhre jr vice president and general counsel for 
anheuserbusch said three employees were responsible for the 
pollution violations and acted without the consent or knowledge of 
the company two were fired and one was allowed to resign he said 
we are a highly regulated industry and we do not accept any 
excuse not to adhere to the law said suhre 
criminal charges could be brought against individuals involved in 
the pollution and coverup abrams said but he declined to identify 
those under investigation 
the pollution had no permanent environmental impact but may have 
contributed to an overall lessening of water quality in the river 
said state environmental conservation commissioner thomas jorling 
excessive amounts of phosphorus can result in weed and algae growth 
that can hinder the development of fish and other aquatic life 
suhre said no completely untreated waste was discharged directly 
into the river 
the dec investigation stemmed from a tip from a fired employee 
the state officials charged that anheuserbusch treatment plant 
employees began submitting false monitoring reports on discharges 
into the seneca river in 1982 
