<TEXT>
a bipartisan group of senators including the 
majority leader unveiled legislation today rivaling president 
bushs proposal for improving air quality in smogchoked cities 
the bill would like the bush measure tighten automobile 
emissions requirements but does not include two key elements of the 
presidents proposal a forced switch from todays gasoline to 
cleanburning motor fuels in severely polluted cities and 
permission for automakers to average emissions by engine category to 
comply with antipollution requirements 
instead the rival measure would require each car to meet the 
emissions standards as under current law and would allow 
automakers to choose whether to build cars for alternative fuels or 
reduce pollution in other ways 
the legislation like the bush measure sets new deadlines 
ranging from 5 to 20 years for cities to clean up their smog 
problems but the placement of cities in the various categories 
would be different 
i expect this bill will cut auto emissioins by 50 percent by 
the year 2000 said chief sponsor max baucus dmont adding that 
the bush plan wont get us across the finish line in improving 
air quality 
the bill was cosponsored by sen john chafee rri the 
ranking republican on the senate environment committee and was 
strongly endorsed by majority leader george j mitchell dmaine 
in setting new ozone deadlines 101 geographical areas failed to 
meet the nowexpired cleanup timetables the new legislation would 
only give los angeles 20 years to clean up its ozone problem the 
bush legislation would allow three others areas new york city 
houston and gary ind to take 20 years 
the baucus legislation would give those three cities 15 years 
but like the bush measure would force those with the longest 
extensions to institute the most severe antipollution measures 
the bush measure is before the house energy and commerce 
environment subcommittee which will consider amendments next week 
chafee is not only cosponsoring the baucus bill but also is the 
chief senate sponsor of the bush legislation 
chafees agreement to back the baucus ozone provisions places him 
at odds with parts of the bush plan which had backing from only 
three democratic senators when it was introduced last month 
asked why hes backing two bills with conflicting provisions 
chafee said he agrees with the baucus approach for ozone reduction 
the senator said he agreed to sponsor the administration bill even 
though he doesnt back some of its provisions because it was the 
first effort an administration has made in eight years to tackle 
the nations air quality problem 
former president reagan did not propose a comprehensive clean air 
revision during his two terms in office 
it marks the second time in two days that a chief sponsor of the 
bush clean air bill has signaled disagreement with a major portion 
of the legislation 
on thursday the chief democratic sponsor in the house rep john 
d dingell dmich expressed strong reservations with bushs 
proposed cap on future emissions of sulfur dioxide the chief 
ingredient of acid rain the limit would make it difficult for 
utilities the main source of acid rain to grow and take on new 
customers dingell argued 
baucus said his legislation would tighten tailpipe standards for 
autos with the goal of cutting car pollution in half by the year 
2000 
but it would not force use of cleanburning motor vehicle fuels 
in severely polluted cities 
the bush administration calls its clean fuels program the most 
innovative and farreaching component of its ozonecutting 
proposals the administration would force a portion of the car fleet 
in the most seriously polluted cities to operate on clean burning 
fuels such as methanol ethanol natural gas electricity propane 
or reformulated gasoline 
the president wants a sale schedule for such vehicles beginning 
with 500000 cars sold nationally in the 1995 model year and going 
up to one million cars in the model years 1997 through 2004 
the baucus proposal would give automakers discretion in deciding 
how to reduce car pollution and hand them the option of using clean 
fuels or other methods 
i dont think its wise to mandate change in the marketplace so 
that certain users have to use certain kinds of cars baucus said 
