<DOCNO> AP890915-0106 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
sweeney todd is stephen sondheims most 
relentless and uncompromising musical a brilliant but chilling tale 
of revenge 
that chill permeated the original 1979 production from demonic 
performances by len cariou and angela lansbury to harold princes 
brechtian direction to the mammoth black ironfoundry sets of 
eugene and franne lee 
now in an intimate revival which opened thursday at broadways 
circle in the square director susan schulman has sought to 
humanize if not soften the story and its leading characters the 
change makes for a remarkable reworking of what is still the most 
unnerving musical ever to reach broadway 
this is a much more personal sweeney todd than the original 
which seemed at times to be more an indictment of the industrial 
revolution for what it had done to british society than the story of 
real people 
sorrow and even a little pity for todd and his cohorts creep into 
the bloodthirsty goingson at the circle in the square thats 
something the brutal but effective original production didnt allow 
hugh wheelers underrated book taken from an adaptation by 
british playwright edward bond seems better than it was 10 years 
ago a model of compression it tells of todd a barber who returns 
to london after an unjust exile and imprisonment in australia he 
finds his wife gone and his daughter the ward of the lascivious 
judge turpin 
todd plots revenge with the help of mrs lovett a dotty maker of 
meat pies the barber slits the throats of his customers and their 
corpses provide fresh ingredients for mrs lovetts delicacies 
much of what schulman has accomplished has been dictated by the 
intheround playing area the show began life last spring at the 
york theater company a tiny offoffbroadway troupe which uses an 
east side school gymnasium for its productions on broadway the 
director and set designer james morgan surround the audience with 
scenery a panorama of london tenements of the late 19th century 
covers the theaters walls so do clotheslines of drying laundry 
at one end of the stage sprawls mrs lovetts pie shop and at the 
other the home of judge turpin in between the cobblestone streets 
of london become the arena for much of the crowd action a fog 
machine works overtime to create the right smoky atmosphere 
bob guntons portrayal of the title character echoes the len 
cariou original his voice may not be as strong as carious but his 
acting has more range 
there are more changes in the character of mrs lovett seen here 
as a woman willing to do anything for love rather than the grotesque 
comic figure so wonderfully portrayed by lansbury beth fowler is a 
softer giddier mrs lovett than her predecessor shes also a 
better singer and gives a sweeter emphasis to such comic songs as 
by the sea and the worst pies in london 
sondheims monumental score is a study in contrasts haunting 
melodies such as not while im around johanna and pretty 
woman clash with much harsher numbers such as the ballad of 
sweeney todd epiphany and city on fire 
the supporting cast must grapple with some of the most difficult 
songs in the show there are expert portraits and some notable 
singing by david barron as the evil judge and michael mccarty as the 
porcine beadle 
also turning in fine work are jim walton as anthony the young 
sailor in love with todds daughter johanna and eddie korbich as 
tobias mrs lovetts young assistant in the pie shop korbich 
delivers a touching version of not while im around the lullaby 
tobias sings to mrs lovett but bill nabel misses the comedy of 
pirelli todds illfated italian competitor and gretchen kingsley 
as johanna sings harshly 
sweeney todd originally succeeded as a largescale 
combination of grand guignol and melodrama it was a horror story 
that didnt allow the audience to get close to the characters by 
reducing the scale schulman does and makes the show more 
effective and more unsettling her villains are much more vulnerable 
and everyday normal 
at the end of the musical when the actors turn and point their 
fingers at the audience schulman makes the point that there may be 
a little bit of sweeney todd lurking in all of us 
what other critics said 
frank rich the new york times by forcing us to face mr 
sondheims music and the feelings it contains so intensely ms 
schulman doesnt obliterate the prince production she creates an 
alternative such is the depth of mr sondheims achievement that 
sweeney todd can support radically different interpretations 
linda winer new york newsday the show is a fast raging 
beautifully bittersweet and deliciously junky grand guignol 
don nelsen daily news todd is too long at 2 hours and 55 
minutes but its music and performances are worth it 
</TEXT>
