<TEXT>
early detection and treatment of those infected 
with the aids virus may help avert one of the most serious epidemics 
of our time but the cost of doing so may push the us health 
system into chaos medical researchers said today 
the cost of finding and treating those who carry the virus but 
are not yet ill could reach 5 billion or more a yearwith urban 
areas the hardest hit researchers reported in todays journal of 
the american medical association 
while the economic challenge of early intervention is 
substantial for hardhit regions it can be managed if the federal 
government takes on greater financial responsibility said the 
researchers from new yorks montefiore medical center and the 
universities of north carolina and california 
recent advances in the treatment of those infected with the virus 
but who do not yet have fullfledged cases of aids make a compelling 
case for expanding early treatment said the researchers led by 
montefiores peter arno 
because of new antiviral therapies that slow the disease and 
drugs that can prevent a common form of pneumonia associated with 
the disease early detection may slow the fatal diseases progress 
the researchers said 
they suggested that policymakers devise a strategy that expands 
the capabilities of hospitalaffiliated outpatient clinics to 
accommodate better patient monitoring and increased counseling 
the authors estimate that the annual cost for a patient with no 
symptoms would be about 854 until drug intervention is needed once 
drugs and increased medical care are needed a midrange estimate 
would be about 9600 annually they said 
if treatment were available to half of those infected with the 
hiv virus today the cost would be more than 48 billion assuming 
more than 1 million people currently carry the virus but are not yet 
diagnosed with aids 
the article also suggested overpricing by drug companies accounts 
for a large portion of early treatment costs drug therapy will 
account for approximately 80 percent of the cost of early 
intervention they said 
one companys ability to market a drug without price restraints 
has led to a quadrupling of its parent companys stock it said 
although drug companies have a legitimate need to recoup their 
research investments the public expects reasonable prices for 
lifesaving drugs they wrote 
