<TEXT>
industrial production recorded its biggest gain 
in four months in august the government said friday in a report 
that drew mixed reaction to the 03 percent gain 
the federal reserve board said the august production rate 
followed revised increases of 01 percent in july and 02 percent in 
june after remaining flat in may 
the fed originally had reported production rose 02 percent in 
july but fell 01 percent in both may and june production was up 
07 percent in april 
thats not only stronger than expected but the revisions were 
substantial the economy never really slowed down said michael k 
evans of evans economics inc a washington consulting firm 
however william k macreynolds forecasting director of the us 
chamber of commerce said the gain was only 28 percent over august 
of last year after rising 57 percent in 1988 
growth in the manufacturing sector has been sluggish throughout 
1989 falling farther behind the growth in the services sector he 
said 
the fed credited almost all the august growth to a rebound in 
production at auto factories and a pickup in coal mining following a 
strike 
excluding motor vehicles output of both consumer goods and 
business equipment was sluggish during the summer it said 
at the same time the central bank reported that the operating 
rate of the nations factories mines and utilities remained 
unchanged at 838 percent of capacity in august the operating rate 
measures not only output but also changes in productivity levels 
factory use had declined 01 percentage point in june the 
central bank said the rate had hit a 10year high of 843 percent 
in december 1988 and last january last months operating rate also 
was unchanged from august 1988 
unchanged capacity utilization in august signals the likelihood 
that inflationary pressures have declined substantially in the last 
several months macreynolds said 
the closer us industry gets to full operating capacity the 
greater difficulty it has producing enough to meet demand leading 
to shortages and price increases analysts generally consider an 
operating rate of 85 percent or above as an indication of 
inflationary pressures 
the federal reserve has been walking a fine line of keeping 
interest rates high enough to cool inflationary pressures without 
slowing growth so much that the economy slides into a recession 
industrial production at manufacturing plants making both durable 
and nondurable goods rose 02 percent last month after remaining 
flat in july and increasing 03 percent in june output was up 23 
percent at mines and oil wells but fell 1 percent at utilities 
the fed said its industrial production index in august stood at 
1424 percent of its 1977 base up from 142 percent in july 
at the same time the operating rate rose 01 percentage point to 
84 percent at manufacturing plants the rate had peaked at 847 
percent in january 
the rate at factories producing durable goods bigticket items 
expected to last more than three years rose 02 percentage point 
to 826 percent the rate at factories producing nondurable goods 
fell from 864 percent in july to 861 percent in august 
 
