<TEXT>
the senate deliberating less than an hour 
approved a 77 billion military construction bill friday that 
eliminates president bushs request for work on bases in south korea 
and the philippines 
the best way to make our defense dollar go further is to secure 
a more equitable burden sharing from our allies sen jim sasser 
dtenn chairman of the senate appropriations subcommitte on 
military construction said prior to the chambers overwhelming 
approval of the bill 
the vote was 931 with sen mark hatfield rore the lone 
dissenter 
overall the bill covering the fiscal year that begins oct 1 
provides 13 billion less than this years level for military 
construction and about 300 million less than bush had requested 
the senate blueprint also differs from the house version which 
totals 87 billion including 500 million for base closings that 
the senate has put in the separate defense appropriations bill 
members of the senate and the house will meet later this month to 
fashion a compromise 
prior to the vote sasser told his colleagues that uncertainity 
regarding the level of us forces overseas led to major cuts in the 
legislation 
this bill provides for no new military construction on the 
korean peninsula due to disputes and discussions its unwise to 
move forward with any new construction sasser said 
the legislation cuts 855 million from the 863 million bush 
requested for south korea the house earmarked 742 million for 
construction there 
several members of congress have called for reductions in the 
43000 us personnel stationed in south korea 
sens bennett johnston dla and dale bumpers dark on 
thursday proposed a reduction of 3000 troops during committee 
consideration of the defense spending bill but later withdrew their 
amendment the lawmakers indicated they would introduce the measure 
when the full senate took up the bill 
the united states spends 26 billion a year to maintain its 
troops in south korea 
sasser said the decision to cut all 408 million the president 
requested for the philippines was based on upcoming negotiations on 
a new treaty to replace the military bases agreement 
the usphilippines pact under which the united states leases 
clark air base and subic bay naval base will expire in september 
1991 
philippine president corazon aquino has refused to say whether 
she favors keeping the us bases but a philippine senate 
resolution introduced last month seeks to close the bases 
mrs aquino is expected to discuss the issue when she visits 
washington in november 
while cutting money for overseas projects the subcommittee added 
250 million to the bill for the national guard and reserves in the 
united states bush had requested 4526 million 
the subcommittee also cut 50 million from the presidents 
request of 1015 million for housing the b2 stealth bomber at the 
whiteman air force base in missouri the reduction mirrors the 
action taken in the authorization bill and reflects the delay in the 
program 
sasser in recommending approval of the legislation said the 
bill continues the priorities adopted over the last several years 
and provides adequately for our most pressing military construction 
needs 
</TEXT>
