<TEXT>
the huge store of information in the library of 
congress could be made available to libraries and scholars across 
the country through an improved computer network the nations chief 
librarian said friday 
the library of congress and the national library community want 
to help develop a national research and education network james 
h billington the librarian of congress told a senate subcommittee 
the major information resources for this nation reside in the 
library of congress and other research libraries across the country 
these collections have been assembled in many cases with federal 
state and local revenues 
our citizens have a right to expect that these irreplaceable 
intellectual resources be made ever more widely available through a 
national information network he said 
billington testified in favor of a bill sponsored by sen al 
gore dtenn which calls for the establishment of national 
computerbased research network gore chairs the senate commerce 
science subcommittee which held fridays hearing 
books would be stored digitally on magnetic tape compact discs 
or on computers gore said using a computer library patrons 
could access information from the books in the librarys collection 
thousands of books could be online available at the touch of 
a button gore said adding that the technology already exists 
the library of congress with 88 million items is the largest 
collection of recorded and printed information ever assembled in a 
single place billington said 
one of the questions that needs to be resolved before the 
nationwide network is built is how to ensure copyright protection 
the association of american publishers told the panel 
use of public domain materials only could create an expectation 
in the user community that any information in the system could be 
used freely without regard to copyright the group said in a 
statement 
