president carlos salinas de gortari says 
he will help a us coalition of hispanic leaders form a binational 
commission to address problems facing residents on both sides of the 
border 
intent on solidifying ties with mexico the organization impacto 
2000 met with salinas for 45 minutes thursday night to outline their 
plan it was salinas first trip to baja california since he took 
office dec 1 
the proposal would create cooperatives to deal with crossborder 
issues including commerce education immigration culture and 
health care 
saying positive changes already are occurring in several of those 
areas in mexico the president told 300 delegates of the group that 
he welcomed the plan and would direct various mexican agencies to 
begin preparing the framework to deal with some of the issues 
we will continue to work we have a good relationship with the 
us government and the congress and an especially harmonious 
relationship with the mexicanamerican community salinas said 
we will continue that relationship with the future generations of 
mexicanamericans 
the coalition which wants to spur progress on these problems by 
the year 2000 includes representatives from churches immigration 
centers hispanic elected officials and hispanic professional and 
student groups such as the league of united latin american citizens 
and the gi forum 
the proposal submitted to salinas seeks to create a binational 
commission that would include mexican agencies and leaders from 
those business education church student and labor sectors it 
excludes the us government 
armando navarro director of the san bernardino califbased 
institute for social justice said the us government was left out 
because it has underestimated americas relationship with mexico for 
too long 
however impacto realizes that the growing hispanic population in 
the united states is an issue that has to be addressed navarro said 
about 20 million hispanics live in the united states today 62 
percent of them born there navarro said he said projections 
indicate half of californias residents by 2030 will be hispanic 
members of the 4yearold coalition met with salinas last year 
and the president promised to listen to their proposal after he was 
elected 
