<DOCNO> AP890915-0157 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
richard herzfelder now the aps news editor for 
mexico and central america has known robert penn warren since 1972 
when he studied under him at yale university 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the cancer that would kill him was already at 
work he couldnt lift weights or walk young men and women into 
breathlessness any more 
but robert penn warren refused to be a sick man he didnt want 
to talk about that he was the first poet laureate of the united 
states and he had a speech to write 
i drove him and his wife eleanor from his summer home in 
stratton vt to a hospital in boston even about that there was a 
sense of adventure would we get lost stuck in a snowbank there 
could be no such thing as disaster 
he told me his daughter rosanna had been born at home during a 
snowstorm no doctors could get to the house that was an adventure 
too but perhaps only in retrospect 
we discussed poetry the news war and rock music you couldnt 
be depressed around him it seemed silly 
mr warren i never called him anything else though his 
nickname was red for the red hair of his youth was generous 
enough to let me think of him as a friend 
i took the last class he taught at yale a writing course given 
in the fall of 1972 he was 67 then the author of all the kings 
men what more could he do i thought that was a book from the 
1940s 
at first it was awful he was an oldfashioned teacher he didnt 
like fools and didnt seem to believe in giveandtake in the 
classroom sometimes he looked like a crocodile 
then he read rudyard kiplings story the man who would be 
king to the class it was amazing that his highpitched kentucky 
accent he never lost it despite years in california england new 
england could recreate the dry mountains of northern pakistan 
he invited the class to his house for dinner introduced us to 
leading literary lights this is john cheever john hersey ralph 
ellison 
i was drinking bourbon because i didnt want to seem like a wimp 
nervous i emptied my glass quickly you look like you need a 
drink he said refilling my glass 
after about six of those i went downstairs and took a nap on the 
dining room floor thats where i was when the first guests walked 
in for supper 
he liked that he came from a generation that thought it romantic 
to drink to oblivion daily though he cut down in later years i 
stayed up with him a couple of times what i couldnt do was get up 
the next morning lift weights and take a twomile walk then it was 
time to work 
work people who telephoned him in the morning got an awful 
shock hed answer but you were interrupting work he didnt much 
like telephones anyway he once wrote a poem called little black 
heart of the telephone 
at the time i didnt understand why that might be important i 
didnt understand how easy it was to lose time how hard it is to 
concentrate and get more than three things done in a day how hard 
it was for a man to keep producing after winning two pulitzer prizes 
he retired from yale then he won his third pulitzer he 
didnt particularly need it what he needed was the work 
mr warren taught me a lot of things few of them in class he 
taught by example by his energy by his love of truth and beauty 
by his sense of adventure 
he and his wife taught me and many others that its possible for 
two competitive people to love each other and have a happy marriage 
mrs warren writes under the name eleanor clark their tennis court 
is a memorial to the national book award it was built with her 
prize money none of those prizes stopped them from wearing funny 
hats on new years eve 
there is a final memory my favorite he told me later hed 
thought i was his stupidest student because i never talked in class 
finally he called me in for a private conference 
somehow i mentioned that i had just read alfred tennysons poem 
ulysses for the first time the last line has become a cliche 
but i thought it was stunning when read as the climax to a great 
poem 
he almost leaped out of his chair and yelped its a 
magnificent poem 
i started reciting the first lines planning to make some learned 
comment or rather some comment that would make me seem learned 
instead he simply joined me together we recited the whole poem 
i could not believe i was remembering it all but it seemed easy 
the poem describes ulysses years after the trojan wars and his 
10year homeward odyssey old but still determined to push on to new 
adventure in spite of all risk trouble or weakness 
i didnt realize how much that might have meant to mr warren 
until just now this is how it ends 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
though much is taken much abides and though 
we are not now that strength which in old days 
moved earth and heaven that which we are we are 
one equal temper of heroic hearts 
made weak by time and fate but strong in will 
to strive to seek to find and not to yield 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
