<TEXT>
the state department registered on friday its 
continuing concern that north korea may be developing nuclear 
weapons but said it was unaware of any development that would 
heighten the concern 
earlier the south korean news agency yonhap quoted a department 
official as saying the us government was gravely concerned and 
was keeping a close watch on possible efforts to develop nuclear 
weapons 
the news agency quoted spencer richardson the head of the 
departments korea section as saying the soviet union would be as 
concerned if north korea produced such weapons 
while denying it has nuclear weapons north korea has repeatedly 
charged that us forces based in south korea were equipped with 
nuclear arms and were preparing for a nuclear war on the divided 
korean peninsula us officials have rejected the north korean 
claims 
the united states garrisons about 43000 troops in south korea 
under a defense pact the soviet union is the communist norths main 
arms supplier 
asked about the yonhap report richard boucher the state 
department spokesman said i dont have anything new to express 
our concern 
he added i think weve talked very often in our past about the 
need for north korea to put its nuclear programs under international 
safeguards they reached some sort of agreement way back in 1985 
with the international atomic energy agency that they would do that 
but so far the actual safeguards provisions have not been completed 
and we really think they should do that at a very early date 
asked if there was some new reason for special concern the us 
