<TEXT>
an allout war against screwworms has been 
launched in puerto rico to help prevent the livestock pests from 
migrating to the united states the agriculture department said 
friday 
james w glosser administrator of the departments animal and 
plant health inspection service said about 20 screwworm larvae were 
found sept 5 near san juan on a horse that had been shipped from 
venezuela 
beginning friday he said about 800000 sexually sterilized 
screwworm flies will be released twice a week for six weeks in a 
fivemile radius around the airport and the quarantine station 
the technique floods the suspected area with sterile male flies 
if a female mates with one her eggs will not hatch thus ending the 
life cycle normally the eggs are laid in open sores or wounds of 
warmblooded animals hatching out into worms that feed on the 
living flesh 
glosser said the adult screwworm fly is about twice the size of a 
house fly with orange eyes and a bluishgreen body with three dark 
stripes along the back screwworm larvae are creamy white and grow 
to about half an inch in length after five to seven days of feeding 
screwworms were eradicated in puerto rico in 1975 the united 
states was declared free of the pests in 1966 although small 
infestations have occurred since then mostly along the usmexico 
border 
</TEXT>
