<TEXT>
robert penn warren was remembered friday as a son 
of the south who became a citizen of the world as a brilliant poet 
fiction writer teacher and critic and as a nice man 
he was reticent ironic reserved and perfectly charming and i 
loved and respected him quite apart from his work said poet 
howard nemerov who owns a copy of the first edition of warrens 
first book 
he had such vigor and such love of life he was such wonderful 
company he was the soul of hilarity said novelist eudora welty 
whose first work was published in the southern review when warren 
was editor in the 1930s he was a good friend to writers 
constantly generous and giving 
red warren died friday at his summer home in vermont after 
battling cancer for three years in a literary career that spanned 
nearly 60 years he wrote dozens of books and made hundreds of 
friends 
many were colleagues cleanth brooks developed the new 
criticism with warren concentrating on the text of literature 
not the authors lives 
he was one of our truly allaround men who made great 
contributions in all fields he was a great poet fine teacher and 
did something to revolutionize the modes of teaching literature 
said brooks 
others were students pete axthelm the writer and tv commentator 
and a student of warrens at yale in the mid60s recalled sitting 
in his office over morning coffee to discuss comic scenes by 
novelist william faulkner 
i treasure the memory he said when people ask me what the 
best thing about going to yale was i always say robert penn warren 
to listen to this man of the south talk about the great 
southern writer was just an unbelievable privilege i really did 
love this man 
others were officials of institutions with which he was 
affiliated 
james h billington librarian of congress said warrens years 
at the library of congress as consultant in poetry and more recently 
as the nations first poet laureate consultant in poetry were 
marked by extraordinary excellence of achievement his legacy 
promises to be with americans for generations to come 
warren was a wonderfully warm and generous man who is fondly 
remembered by his former students and colleagues said joe b 
wyatt chancellor of vanderbilt university which warren attended as 
an undergraduate and where he joined two important literary 
movements the fugitives and the agrarians 
the fugitives named after a literary magazine argued the 
importance of a southern literary identity the agrarians warned 
against the dangers of industrialization and it was in that 
connection that warren wrote an essay defending segregation he came 
to repudiate that stance 
this was in 1930 he just felt that was then this was now 
said walter sullivan a professor of english at vanderbilt who had 
known warren since the late 1940s 
i think he is going to be read 100 years from now all the 
kings men is already a classic generations have read that 
book sullivan said 
his fellow writers marveled at his versatility and virtuosity 
hes astounding said poet robert bly its very seldom 
that someone can write poetry and fiction and do it well in 
fiction you take nine or ten generations and compress them in 
poetry you take 30 seconds and expand it 
rwb lewis the yale professor who produced an anthology of 
american literature with warren and is writing a book about him 
called warren the greatest person of letters in the country for 
several decades 
he was extraordinarily gifted in so many different ways as a 
novelist as a poet as a literary critic of extraordinary 
influence as a cultural historian said lewis 
but most were more interested in praising his character he was 
all agreed a great storyteller an ardent father his colleague 
allen tate once complained that all warren talked about in his 
letters was his children a voracious reader and hard worker a man 
of high standards 
he wasnt one of these polite gentle postworld war ii 
encouragers of the young said bly a younger poet when he saw 
something that was shoddy he named it whether it was in himself 
or in others 
he was born in kentucky and educated in tennessee and was known 
as a southern writer though he lived much of his life elsewhere 
his work was not confined to any place at all said miss 
welty 
he was a southerner in his manners and in his warmth and in his 
accent said sullivan but he once told me well you know my 
community is the world my friends are all over the world and my 
friends are my community he was a cosmopolitan but he had a lot 
of the south in him 
</TEXT>
