<TEXT>
the volume of world merchandise trade is expected 
to increase by about 7 percent in 1989 and growth will likely remain 
strong in the next few years the organization that sponsors 
tradeliberalizing agreements said today 
in an optimistic report the general agreement on tariffs and 
trade said technological progress the fall in the price of oil and 
new national economic policies were among factors behind 
unexpectedly high recent growth in international commerce 
it said trade in services such as tourism and banking had grown 
even faster than merchandise trade during the 1980s and reached an 
estimated value of about 560 billion last year 
merchandise exports were worth an estimated 288 trillion in 
1988 145 percent higher than the previous year the volume of 
goods traded increased by 85 percent a record for the 1980s the 
report said 
despite the expansion in world trade many third world countries 
suffered a drop in export earnings during the decade the report 
said 
it warned that the worlds poorest countries can no longer rely 
on exports of commodities which account for threequarters of their 
foreign exchange to fuel economic growth 
examining the reasons for the expansion of international 
commerce gatt said one factor was technological innovations that 
have increased the scope of goods and services that can be traded on 
world markets 
the halving of the price of oil since the 1980 peak the rising 
share of manufactured products in trade and the increase in the 
number of international mergers were also responsible the report 
said 
economic reforms in the soviet union and china relatively low 
inflation in western countries deregulation of business and freeing 
of capital movements further combined to boost world trade and open 
up international markets the report said 
in the longer term gatt predicted the world economy may have 
entered a period in which the average growth rates for output and 
trade will be higher than they have been since the onset of 
economic difficulties in the late 1960s and the early 1970s 
gatt spokesman david woods said this forecast covered the next 
five to 10 years 
the 97 nations that belong to the trade forum account for over 
fourfifths of world trade bolivia became a member of gatt last 
