the house ways and means committee has agreed 
to legislation that would siphon off 43 billion over five years 
from profits of companies making ozonedepleting chemicals 
the provision approved thursday was added to a tax and 
entitlement bill 
the bush administration has sought such a revenueraising measure 
because it targets windfall profits that chemical firms could earn 
after an international treaty reduces supplies of 
chlorofluorocarbons 
the socalled cfcs destroy the ozone layer in the stratosphere 
and increase the risk of skin cancer there is similar language 
pending before the senate 
the proposal which the ways and means panel labels a tax on 
ozonedepleting chemicals would bring in an estimated 362 
million in the 1990 fiscal year while revenues in the following 
four years were put respectively at 614 million 753 million 
11 billion and 14 billion the tax would become effective jan 1 
the chemical industry denies there will be windfall profits after 
the united states begins implementing the montreal protocol a 1987 
international agreement to cut production of cfcs 
the theory behind the tax is that demand will far outstrip supply 
once production is frozen at 1986 levels the protocol requires that 
by 1998 production can be only 50 percent of the 1986 figures 
the five manufacturers of cfcs are developing substitutes but 
they are reportedly three to five years away from production 
