michael milkens lawyers say they arent picking 
a fight with the press in an attempt to squelch alleged leaks by 
government prosecutors in the highly publicized securities fraud and 
racketeering case 
in court papers filed this week lawyers for the former drexel 
burnham lambert inc highyield bond division leader claim that a 
constant stream of press leaks is threatening milkens right to a 
fair trial 
the motion asks us district judge kimba wood to order the 
government to stop leaking confidential material hold a hearing to 
identify the sources of the leaks punish the leakers and make 
public a confidential securities and exchange commission memo 
written about in the washington post 
no members of the media would be called at any hearing on the 
motion because we are not interested in confrontations with the 
press the motion adds 
the lawyers claim the government has turned confidential grand 
jury proceedings into a spectator sport by releasing information 
about the milken probe repeatedly over the last three years to 
pressure witnesses and other possible targets to cooperate 
the motion filed wednesday in federal court in manhattan claims 
the alleged leaking flatly violates federal criminal regulations 
and other legal and ethical rules requiring confidentiality in 
government investigations 
we are asking the court to stop the government from continuing 
its leaking and to punish those government officials responsible 
martin flumenbaum a lawyer for milken said thursday 
a hearing to ferret out media leaks would not be unprecedented 
the motion cites the 1980 bank fraud case of former carter 
administration budget director bert lance in which a federal 
appeals court ordered such a hearing 
though the milken motion seeks to exclude reporters motions 
like this have the potential for leading to first amendment 
confrontations with the press according to one prominent first 
amendment attorney who asked not to be identified 
milken his brother lowell and former drexel trader bruce 
newberg were charged march 29 in a 98count fraud and racketeering 
indictment that alleges insider trading securities law violations 
and other crimes in the broadest action of the governments wall 
street crackdown they pleaded innocent and a march 1990 trial is 
set 
milken was first named in news reports as the governments main 
target shortly after nowjailed stock speculator ivan boesky agreed 
to cooperate with prosecutors in late 1986 
newspaper stories since then regularly have contained advance 
details of the governments investigation and indictment plans 
including the charges 
the milken motion cites stories published in the wall street 
journal the new york times the washington post and the los angeles 
times about the case quoting sources close to the investigation 
or people familiar with the governments investigation 
roger may spokesman for dow jones amp co inc which owns the 
wall street journal said the newspaper does not comment on its 
sourcing policies 
our job is to try to find out what people are doing thats 
what we do added martin baron business editor of the los angeles 
times 
the 31page motion states that the government has presented 
and is continuing to present its case to the grand jurors as much 
through the pages of the daily papers as through the testimony of 
witnesses in the grand jury room 
the document cites three recent stories in the post based on a 
confidential may 1988 sec report containing details of secret 
testimony of government witnesses and other articles specifying the 
contents of a new milken indictment expected in october 
the leaks are the result of decisions by some in the government 
to use publicity as a prosecutorial weapon carefully timing the 
disclosures to pressure defendants witnesses and those under 
investigation the motion states 
an sec spokeswoman declined to comment on the memo the us 
attorneys said it would respond to the motion in court 
