the pentagons chief supplier of hydraulic 
aircraft landing gear has agreed to repay the government about 14 
million in contract overcharges for the air forces largest 
transport plane 
the government claimed that labor charges on a 67 million 
contract were twice as high as original estimates by the company 
curtisswright of ridgefield nj said us attorney samuel a 
alito jr 
the contract was for 60 spare landing gear actuators that control 
landing gear flaps and other moveable exterior systems on the air 
forces lockheed c5a galaxy 
alito said the companys failure to provide air force auditors 
with labor standards and data on the companys internal cost 
estimates led to a gross inflation of the labor costs 
curtisswright has denied any wrongdoing attempts to reach 
corporate officials after the settlement was announced thursday 
evening were unsuccessful and the switchboard at the companys 
headquarters was closed 
the government contends curtisswrights contract was based on a 
company estimate of 46000 labor hours for the contract alito said 
investigators found the contract was completed in 23000 hours 
the companys failure to live up to its certification with 
respect to the c5a flight actuators subjected it to civil 
liability alito said in a statement 
under the false claims act a civil warera statute aimed at 
wartime profiteers the government can demand reimbursement when it 
can prove a contractor was not negotiated in good faith the act was 
further bolstered in 1986 by amendments that allow the government to 
claim triple damages and apply large fines 
alito said the claims were not part of criminal or civil court 
proceedings but were the result of a preliminary investigation by 
his office and the defense criminal investigative service an arm of 
the us defense department 
