<TEXT>
mcdonnell douglas corp said friday it would 
modify its dc10 jetliners to ensure safe landings even if all three 
hydraulic systems fail 
the modifications developed in response to a dc10 crash that 
killed 112 people in sioux city iowa last july were greeted 
warmly by james b busey the head of the federal aviation 
administration 
the system design changes proposed by mcdonnell douglas are 
a solid step forward in assuring there will be no repeat of the july 
19 accident busey said in a statement issued in washington dc 
once these design changes are in place they will raise the 
already high safety standards required of the dc10 and in effect 
make a good airplane even better 
douglas aircraft co a division of mcdonnell douglas based in 
long beach manufactured the dc10s which have been replaced by the 
newer but similar md11s 
mcdonnell spokeswoman elayne bendel said in a telephone interview 
that the company had yet to decide whether to make the same 
modifications to its md11s 
we are going to look at the md11 and evaluate it and well do 
what is appropriate there she said and of course we will 
comply with whatever directives the faa issues 
the three hydraulic systems on the planes are designed to be 
redundant that is to operate independently and to back each other 
up in case one fails 
in the july crash the tail engine on the dc10 disintegrated 
knocking out all three hydraulic systems an event a mcdonnell 
douglas release friday called one in a billion 
the pilot lost virtually all control of the plane which exploded 
in flames in a corn field near the runway 
dale warren a vice president of douglas aircraft co who headed 
the investigation of the crash said the following modifications 
will be made 
an electrically operated shutoff valve will be installed in the 
supply line and a check valve in the return line of the no 3 
hydraulic system 
a check valve will be installed in the no 3 hydraulic reservoir 
a cockpit light will be added to alert the crew if the shutoff 
valve is activated 
the new fastacting shutoff valve located just behind the back 
wall of the cabin will close automatically and the cockpit light 
will come on if a sensor detects hydraulic fluid dropping below a 
preset level in the reservoir 
even if all three hydraulic systems are affected by severe damage 
to the tail section as happened in sioux city the valve will stop 
fluid flow through the no 3 system warren said 
with adequate hydraulic pressure thus preserved in that system 
the crew should have enough control to fly the plane to a safe 
landing 
</TEXT>
