the struggle over control of new 
hampshires largest electric utility settled on four companies 
friday as the deadline passed for filing bankruptcy reorganization 
plans 
public service company of new hampshire which filed for 
bankruptcy protection in january 1988 announced its plan to retain 
control tuesday and formally filed the proposal with the bankruptcy 
court early friday afternoon 
several hours later united illuminating of connecticut became 
the fourth to add its name to the list 
northeast utilities connecticuts largest electric utility and 
new england electric system of westborough mass filed their plans 
earlier 
the united illuminating plan proposed a merger with public 
service the only plan to do so it also called for electricity rate 
increases of 55 percent a year for seven years for public service 
customers matching the rates proposed by public service and 
northeast utilities if seabrook operates 
the new england electric plan called for increases of 48 percent 
during that period 
new hampshire gov judd gregg endorsed the northeast plan when it 
was introduced in july but then switched allegiance this week to 
new england electric because of the lower rates 
but charles bayless public service financial vice president 
called his utility the favorite to retain control because its plan 
already has the approval of shareholders and creditors public 
service also needs only state regulators approval for its plan he 
said 
the other utilities still would have to reach agreement with 
shareholders and creditors and get approval from the securities and 
exchange commission and the federal energy regulatory commission 
something bayless said could prolong the bankruptcy case for two 
more years 
the fact that public services payoff to creditors and 
shareholders would be in securities while some of the other 
proposals offered cash or a combination did not deter bayless 
to our creditors getting paper in april is a heckuva lot 
better than getting cash a year or two later he said 
the next step in the bankruptcy case will be hearings on the four 
plans which federal bankruptcy judge james yacos hopes to conclude 
by midnovember then creditors and shareholders would vote on their 
choice and yacos would make the final decision 
public service with almost 400000 customers filed for 
bankruptcy under the burden of its 36 percent share of the 62 
billion seabrook nuclear plant negotiations have dragged on since 
then for a reorganization plan that would satisfy creditors 
shareholders and the state 
public service has the largest share of seabrook which has been 
completed for three years but has been unable to get a commercial 
