<TEXT>
in an apparent effort to soften the impact of 
travel bargains offered to fall vacationers several major airlines 
have raised a type of discount fare popular with business travelers 
this past week the airlines hiked supercoach oneway fares 
favored by business fliers because they have more lenient 
advancepurchase requirements than cheaper discount fares and dont 
require a saturdaynight stay 
the supercoach fares usually 15 percent to 40 percent below 
standard economy fares were raised by around 20 for a oneway 
ticket 
for example united airlines lowest supercoach fare from new 
york to minneapolis has been increased from 221 one way to 241 a 
threeday advancepurchase fare on american airlines from dallas to 
boston was boosted from 269 to 289 
the action appears aimed at recovering part of the revenue lost 
from the big industrywide fare cuts for the fall season announced in 
midaugust at that time the carriers extended summer travel 
bargains and cut roundtrip fares by as much as 160 to lure 
passengers in the historically weak autumn season most fares to 
europe were reduced by 100 into next spring 
but the latest increases effect is akin to putting a finger in 
the dike some analysts believe 
the carriers are desperately trying to salvage a very serious 
problem that has occurred said julius maldutis who follows the 
airline industry for salomon brothers inc they have had a massive 
erosion in yield any fare actions that are taken now are 
basically to stem the damage 
an airlines yield which reflects the average price of a ticket 
paid by a passenger for each mile flown has become the name of the 
game in the competitive climate of the nations airline industry 
the increase was started by midway airlines an aggressive 
midsized carrier based in chicago that is paying 210 million to 
buy 16 dc9 aircraft as well as gates and other airport facilities 
in philadelphia washington and new york from strikebound eastern 
airlines midway upped its supercoach fares wednesday by 10 one 
way 
the bigger carriers including united american trans world 
airlines delta air lines continental airlines and usair group 
inc quickly matched the move but they raised the fares by 20 
some airlines raised supercoach fares only in a few cities they 
serve to match competitors while others made widespread boosts 
usair spokesman david shipley for example said that carrier was 
increasing the fares in markets all over the country but delta 
is making the change only in a very very few selected markets 
said spokesman jim lundy 
eastern is considering some selective increases said 
spokesman robin matell in miami 
continental like eastern a subsidiary of texas air corp had 
proposed six weeks ago eliminating many supercoach fares but 
the move wasnt matched by competitors and it dropped the idea 
it was an effort on our part to simplify the oneway fare 
structure said ned walker a continental spokesman in houston 
</TEXT>
